==Background== The Nyūtabaru Plateau is at an elevation of about 70 meters on the left bank of the Hitotsuse River that flows southeast from Hitotsuse Dam through Saito City and into the [[Hyūga Sea]]. The plateau contains 207 known burial mounds of various sizes and types. These are divided into four groups based on their distribution and construction period, and from the east to west are name the Tsukahara Kofun Cluster, Ishifune Kofun Cluster, Yamanobo Kofun Cluster, and Gionbara Kofun Cluster. The Gionbara group, where the ''kofun'' are most concentrated, consists of 139 {{nihongo|''empun''|円墳}}-style round tumuli, 14 keyhole-shaped {{nihongo|''zenpō-kōen-fun''|前方後円墳}}, one square {{nihongo|''hōfun''|方墳|1=Square Kofun}}-style tumulus, and one tumulus of unknown shape. One of the ''[[zenpō-kōen-fun]]'', the Mukadezuka Kofun (Nyūtabaru No.58) has a length of 80 meters, and had one 1000 ''[[haniwa]]'', and of unique designs not found in other burial mounds. It is thought to have been built in the 6th century (late Kofun period). <ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=4311750404}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
The area is approximately 15 minutes by car from [[Hyūga-Shintomi Station]] on the [[JR Kyushu]] [[Nippō Main Line]].<ref name="Shiseki"/>
